nagiosNotify.name: nagiosNotify
nagiosNotify.contactinfo: Subhendu Ghosh Telephone: +1 201 232 2851 Email: sghosh@users.sourceforge.net Nagios Information: http://www.nagios.org
nagiosNotify.description: Objects for Nagios(tm) events. There are 2 primary tables reflecting the division in Nagios for Host events and Service events. The event tables are extended by the HostNotifyTable and the ServiceNotifyTable to keep track of the notifications based on events. The tables entries themselves are not accessible but are used for OID entries for TRAP/INFORM notifications. These objects are based on the macros defined in Nagios v2.0

nHostEventIndex.name: nHostEventIndex
nHostEventIndex.description: This object uniquely identifies this host event entry. It is generated by the SNMP application and is not related to any Nagios data.

nHostname.name: nHostname
nHostname.description: Hostname as specified in the Nagios configuration file.

nHostAlias.name: nHostAlias
nHostAlias.description: The host alias as specified in the Nagios configuration file

nHostStateID.name: nHostStateID
nHostStateID.description: The host state as defined by the HOSTSTATEID macro

nHostStateType.name: nHostStateType
nHostStateType.description: The host state as defined by the HOSTSTATETYPE macro

nHostAttempt.name: nHostAttempt
nHostAttempt.description: The number of the current host check retry. For instance, if this is the second time that the host is being rechecked, this will be the number two. Current attempt number is really only useful when writing host event handlers for soft states that take a specific action based on the host retry number. The host state as defined by the HOSTSTATEID macro

nHostDurationSec.name: nHostDurationSec
nHostDurationSec.description: A number indicating the number of seconds that the host has spent in its current state

nHostGroupName.name: nHostGroupName
nHostGroupName.description: The short name of the hostgroup that this host belongs to. This value is taken from the hostgroup_name directive in the hostgroup definition. If the host belongs to more than one hostgroup this macro will contain the name of just one of them.

nHostLastCheck.name: nHostLastCheck
nHostLastCheck.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time at which a check of the host was last performed.

nHostLastChange.name: nHostLastChange
nHostLastChange.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time the host last changed state.

nHostLastUp.name: nHostLastUp
nHostLastUp.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time at which the host was last detected as being in an UP state.

nHostLastDown.name: nHostLastDown
nHostLastDown.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time at which the host was last detected as being in an DOWN state.

nHostLastUnreachable.name: nHostLastUnreachable
nHostLastUnreachable.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time at which the host was last detected as being in an UNREACHABLE state.

nHostOutput.name: nHostOutput
nHostOutput.description: The text output from the last host check (i.e. Ping OK).

nHostPerfData.name: nHostPerfData
nHostPerfData.description: This object contains any performance data that may have been returned by the last host check.

nagiosHostNotifyEntry.name: nagiosHostNotifyEntry
nagiosHostNotifyEntry.description: Nagios host notifications extends the nagiosHostEventTable when a notification is generated for an event.

nHostNotifyType.name: nHostNotifyType
nHostNotifyType.description: This identifies the type of notification that is being sent (PROBLEM, RECOVERY, ACKNOWLEDGEMENT, FLAPPINGSTART or FLAPPINGSTOP)

nHostNotifyNum.name: nHostNotifyNum
nHostNotifyNum.description: This identifies the current notification number for the service or host. The notification number increases by one (1) each time a new notification is sent out for a host or service (except for acknowledgements). The notification number is reset to 0 when the host or service recovers (after the recovery notification has gone out). Acknowledgements do not cause the notification number to increase.

nHostAckAuthor.name: nHostAckAuthor
nHostAckAuthor.description: A string containing the name of the user who acknowledged the host problem. This macro is only valid in notifications where the $NOTIFICATIONTYPE$ macro is set to ACKNOWLEDGEMENT.

nHostAckComment.name: nHostAckComment
nHostAckComment.description: A string containing the acknowledgement comment that was entered by the user who acknowledged the host problem. This macro is only valid in notifications where the $NOTIFICATIONTYPE$ macro is set to ACKNOWLEDGEMENT

nSvcEventIndex.name: nSvcEventIndex
nSvcEventIndex.description: This object uniquely identifies this service event entry

nSvcHostname.name: nSvcHostname
nSvcHostname.description: Hostname as specified in the Nagios configuration file.

nSvcHostAlias.name: nSvcHostAlias
nSvcHostAlias.description: The host alias as specified in the Nagios configuration file

nSvcHostStateID.name: nSvcHostStateID
nSvcHostStateID.description: A number that corresponds to the current state of the service: 0=OK, 1=WARNING, 2=CRITICAL, 3=UNKNOWN.

nSvcHostStateType.name: nSvcHostStateType
nSvcHostStateType.description: Whether the host is in a hard or soft state.

nSvcDesc.name: nSvcDesc
nSvcDesc.description: This value is taken from the description directive of the service definition.

nSvcStateID.name: nSvcStateID
nSvcStateID.description: A number that corresponds to the current state of the service: 0=OK, 1=WARNING, 2=CRITICAL, 3=UNKNOWN

nSvcAttempt.name: nSvcAttempt
nSvcAttempt.description: The number of the current service check retry. For instance, if this is the second time that the service is being rechecked, this will be the number two. Current attempt number is really only useful when writing service event handlers for soft states that take a specific action based on the service retry number.

nSvcDurationSec.name: nSvcDurationSec
nSvcDurationSec.description: A number indicating the number of seconds that the service has spent in its current state.

nSvcGroupName.name: nSvcGroupName
nSvcGroupName.description: The short name of the servicegroup that this service belongs to. This value is taken from the servicegroup_name directive in the servicegroup definition. If the service belongs to more than one servicegroup this object will contain the name of just one of them.

nSvcLastCheck.name: nSvcLastCheck
nSvcLastCheck.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time at which a check of the service was last performed.

nSvcLastChange.name: nSvcLastChange
nSvcLastChange.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time the service last changed state.

nSvcLastOK.name: nSvcLastOK
nSvcLastOK.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time at which the service was last detected as being in an OK state.

nSvcLastWarn.name: nSvcLastWarn
nSvcLastWarn.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time at which the service was last detected as being in a WARNING state.

nSvcLastCrit.name: nSvcLastCrit
nSvcLastCrit.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time at which the service was last detected as being in a CRITICAL state.

nSvcLastUnkn.name: nSvcLastUnkn
nSvcLastUnkn.description: This is a timestamp in time_t format (seconds since the UNIX epoch) indicating the time at which the service was last detected as being in an UNKNOWN state.

nSvcOutput.name: nSvcOutput
nSvcOutput.description: The text output from the last service check (i.e. Ping OK).

nSvcPerfData.name: nSvcPerfData
nSvcPerfData.description: This object contains any performance data that may have been returned by the last service check.

nagiosSvcNotifyEntry.name: nagiosSvcNotifyEntry
nagiosSvcNotifyEntry.description: Nagios service notifications extends the nagiosSvcEnevtsTable when a notification is generated for an event.

nSvcNotifyType.name: nSvcNotifyType
nSvcNotifyType.description: A string identifying the type of notification that is being sent (PROBLEM, RECOVERY, ACKNOWLEDGEMENT, FLAPPINGSTART or FLAPPINGSTOP).

nSvcNotifyNum.name: nSvcNotifyNum
nSvcNotifyNum.description: The current notification number for the service or host. The notification number increases by one (1) each time a new notification is sent out for a host or service (except for acknowledgements). The notification number is reset to 0 when the host or service recovers (after the recovery notification has gone out). Acknowledgements do not cause the notification number to increase.

nSvcAckAuthor.name: nSvcAckAuthor
nSvcAckAuthor.description: A string containing the name of the user who acknowledged the service problem. This object is only valid in notifications where the nSvcNotifyType object is set to ACKNOWLEDGEMENT.

nSvcAckComment.name: nSvcAckComment
nSvcAckComment.description: A string containing the acknowledgement comment that was entered by the user who acknowledged the service problem. This object is only valid in notifications where the nSvcNotifyType object is set to ACKNOWLEDGEMENT.

nHostEvent.name: nHostEvent
nHostEvent.description: The SNMP trap that is generated as a result of an event with the host in Nagios.

nHostNotify.name: nHostNotify
nHostNotify.description: The SNMP trap that is generated as a result of an event requiring notification for a host in Nagios.

nSvcEvent.name: nSvcEvent
nSvcEvent.description: The SNMP trap that is generated as a result of an event with the service in Nagios.

nSvcNotify.name: nSvcNotify
nSvcNotify.description: The SNMP trap that is generated as a result of an event requiring notification for a service in Nagios.
